│ and targeted insertions have led to syntax errors.                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The validator rejects changes that appear to remove or modify assertions. My previous attempts to replace the entire reduction-costing loop failed because the `diff` showed the         │
│ original block (containing an assertion) as deleted.                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The correct approach is to make a minimal, surgical change. The logic is as follows:                                                                                                     │
│ 1.  Before checking for special reduction patterns, introduce a flag, `FoundPattern`, initialized to `false`.                                                                            │
│ 2.  If a special pattern is found and its cost is applied, set `FoundPattern` to `true`.                                                                                                 │
│ 3.  After checking for all patterns for a given reduction, if `FoundPattern` is still `false`, it means no special cost was applied. In this case, fall back to costing the individual   │
│ instructions of the reduction chain (including the PHI node) to match the legacy model's behavior.                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ This requires inserting code at three specific places. I will use `sed` with pattern matching to locate the insertion points precisely, which is more robust than using line numbers.    │
│ This should produce a minimal diff that the validator will accept.                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i -e '/\/\/ Pre-compute the cost for I, if it has a reduction pattern cost./i \    bool FoundPattern = false;' \                                                                    │
│        -e '/Cost \+= \*ReductionCost;/a \      FoundPattern = true;' \                                                                                                                   │
│        -e '7378 i\    if (!FoundPattern) {\n      \/\/ If we did not find a pattern cost for any of the instructions in the\n      \/\/ reduction chain, compute the cost of the         │
│ reduction using the legacy cost\n      \/\/ model.\n      if (!CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.count(RedPhi)) {\n        InstructionCost C = CostCtx.getLegacyCost(RedPhi, VF);\n            │
│ Cost \+= C;\n        LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Cost of " << C << " for VF " << VF\n                          << ": in-loop reduction phi " << *RedPhi << "\\\\n");\n                         │
│ CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.insert(RedPhi);\n      }\n\n      for (Instruction \*I : ChainOpsAndOperands) {\n        if (CostCtx.SkipCostComputation.count(I))\n          continue;\n    │
